{"id":121713,"username":"dmcmahon","name":"","bio":"","cleared":false,"website":null,"location":"","created_at":"2016-11-01T17:24:18.402Z","url":"https://hackerone.com/dmcmahon","anc_triager":false,"hackerone_triager":false,"hackerone_employee":false,"user_type":"legacy","profile_picture_urls":{"small":"/assets/avatars/default-71a302d706457f3d3a31eb30fa3e73e6cf0b1d677b8fa218eaeaffd67ae97918.png","medium":"/assets/avatars/default-71a302d706457f3d3a31eb30fa3e73e6cf0b1d677b8fa218eaeaffd67ae97918.png","xtralarge":"/assets/avatars/default-71a302d706457f3d3a31eb30fa3e73e6cf0b1d677b8fa218eaeaffd67ae97918.png"}}},{"id":7285,"category":"researcher","content":"The application protects against viewing specific information related to other user accounts - this is to protect the confidentiality of other NR customers. New Relic has gotten _very good_ at the way they conceal this info (finding bypasses for this issue has become next to impossible now), but this endpoint I discovered seemed to be accidentally revealing that info once again after a recent code change. \n\nShameless plug of my blog: If you're interested, New Relic has been really awesome and given me permission to talk about some of the vulnerabilities I've found on their program. I've written up a few blog posts about bugs I've found in New Relic, you can read them here: \n\nAbusing internal API to achieve IDOR in New Relic: \nhttps://www.jonbottarini.com/2018/01/02/abusing-internal-api-to-achieve-idor-in-new-relic/\n\nGraphQL abuse: Bypass account level permissions through parameter smuggling:\nhttps://labs.detectify.com/2018/03/14/graphql-abuse/","can_view?":true,"can_create?":false,"attachments":[],"user":{"id":13784,"username":"jon_bottarini","name":"Jon Bottarini","bio":"I ❤️  privilege escalation","cleared":true,"website":"https://www.jonbottarini.com","location":"Austin, TX ","created_at":"2014-11-04T21:03:50.565Z","url":"https://hackerone.com/jon_bottarini","anc_triager":false,"hackerone_triager":false,"hack